<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Renuu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Forgive my newb question here, but can anyone explain the Enstill spell to me?  It works like root, but is more mana intensive and it doesn't last worth squat.  The casters realm description says it stops all movement, which is untrue because then it would be a stun.<P>Thanks!<P>Renuu</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">naxy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Enstill supposedly lasts up to twice as long as Root. But I had the same experience as you with it not holding well when I got it. I used Root until I got Immobilize, which has shorter cast time.<P>------------------<BR>Naxy Dent, Templar of Oasis Covenant on Bristlebane</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Twinskey Bab0linskey</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The first few levels after you get a spell, you tend to fizzle it more then a spell you've had for awhile.  Fizzle and resists would be the main reason I could see anyone calling root "mana intensive".  Mob's that are particulary MR will ofcourse resist more and after root takes; have a higher chance of breaking root at each check.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">varthdadur</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Contrary to what people say, all four root spells have a specific use.<P>L9 Root - I use for soloing the root/DD method.  Its average casting time and low mana cost is perfect.  It lasts long enough for 1 DD to get cast which usually breaks root anyways.  This is also a good traveling spell since you only need to root for a short duration while you run away/atone.  Sometimes I use this spell to root a mob so it attacks the correct tank.  [like last night I had a 53 pally and 56 rogue as melees...needed to root a lot  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"> ]<P>L29 Instill - If I want to park a mob for a decent duration (90 secs I believe) then I use this spell.  Casting time is long but mana is still low.  Lets face it, if i'm parking using this spell it means I probably don't have a chanter in the group.  So the low mana and long root is great.<P>L49 Immobilize - This spell's use is much like the L9 root one.  The difference is it has a better saving throw check so it works against mobs that have higher MR.  At 60 seconds is makes for a decent parking spell.  Also at 1.8 casting time its the quickest casting root which is great against fast and hard hitting mobs.  The mana usage is much more than desired but it you get the root off quickly and without being interrupted you'll save mana on healing yourself the damage you would have been taking on a slower spell.<P>L56? Paralyzing Earth - This baby can root for up to 3 minutes.  Use this when you are soloing with dots.  You can med back the mana from casting this and other spells easily during the duration of this root.  Its slower casting cost and mana use makes it clumsy to use as a parking spell.  Usually you don't need to park a mob for 3 minutes since most mobs are killed in 60 seconds or less.  This spell also shares the saving throw feature of the L49 one in that mobs will have a harder time resisting this spell.<P>I know what I have written might imply that I am memorizing different root spells left and right.  That is not correct.  In each of those situations you know ahead of time which root to keep memorized.<P>Anyone else have any specific uses I have not mentioned?<BR><P>------------------<BR>Baron Varth L60 High Priest<BR>Mogwa L51 Monk</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
